Exploring Red Wine by Reem Hazim

This dataset contains information about red variants of the Portuguese “Vinho Verde” wine. The dataset was created using objective tests on samples of the red wine, such as pH and density. The wine quality is the median score provided by three wine experts, who gave the sample a score between 0 and 10.

There seems to be no wine samples with quality less than 3 or greater than 8. Most samples received a score of 5 or 6, and very few received a 3 or an 8.

There seems to be a gap at around 14.5. Also, the fixed acidity seems to follow a normal distribution, peaking at around 7.5. I wonder if that’s true for volatile acidity as well.

The volatile acidity, on the other hand, seems to follow a bimodal distribution, peaking at 0.4 and 0.6. There is also an outlier with a volatile acidity of almost 1.6. According to the text file, wine with too high volatile acidity will have “an unpleasant, vinegar taste”. This sample must have received a very low score for quality.

It seems like most observations have a value of 0 for citric acid. Looking back at the text file for this dataset, it’s stated that citric acid is “found in small quantities”. Therefore, it makes sense for most samples to have 0 citric acid. We have one outlier, however, that has a citric acid of 1 g/dm^3. There’s also an unusually large amount of observations with a citric acid of almost 0.48 g/dm^3.

The residual sugar histogram seems to be skewed to the right. I’ll apply a log transformation to understand it better. There also seems to be several outliers afetr 9.

There appears to be a normal distribution here, and the transformed distribution peaks at around 2.5.

The chlorides (amount of salt) in the wine appears to have a normal ditribution with many outliers. Let’s zoom in on the plot.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

My dataset has 1599 observations with 13 variables. There is only one ordered factor, wine quality, which is on a scale of 0 - 10, with 0 being worst quality and 10 being best quality. In this dataset, however, none of the samples received lower than a 3 or higher than an 8 for quality.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature of interest in my dataset is the wine quality. I would like to explore how the other variables influence wine quality in my bivariate and multivariate analyses.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

The pH and the volatile and fixed acidity may also have an influence on wine quality. I will explore their relation in my bivariate and multivariate analyses. In addition, the amount of sulphates and the amount of free and total sulfur dioxide might also be dependent on each other, and I’d like to see whether they have an effect on wine quality as well.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

No. Most of my variables are measurements of wine qualities, and there was no room for any of them to be combined. I did, however, change the wine quality data type to an ordered factor to facilitate my analysis.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the
form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

Yes, the alcohol was slightly skewed to the right, even after using log transformation. Sulphates also had a strange distribution, so I used log transformation to change it to a normal distribution. However, it still had many peaks and valleys throughout the distribution because most of the observations fall on certain values.

What stands out to me is that fixed acidity has a moderate positive correlation with citric acidity. I hadn’t considered that before! I will explore their relation further in this section. Moreover, density and fixed acidity also have a moderate positive correlation, while pH and fixed acidity have a negative moderate correlation. I wonder why there isn’t much correlation between pH and volatile acidity, on the other hand.

Alcohol and density seem to have a moderate negative correlation, as shown by the scatter plot and the correlation coefficient. On the other hand, residual sugar has no meaningful relation with alcohol, but it does have a small positive correlation with density.

I will zoom in on the plot by omitting the top 5% of values for residual sugar.

The general trend seems to be that as the amount of residual sugar increases, so does the density. This makes sense, because more residual sugar means more mass, and density is mass/volume. In addition, the vertical lines are due to many observations having the same amount of residual sugar but with different densities.

That seems interesting… Volatile acidity appears to have a strong effect on quality. The samples with the lowest quality have the highest median volatile acidity, while those with the highest quality have the least median volatile acidity. In addition, the interquartile range seems to decrease as the quality increases. I wonder if there’s a similar trend with fixed acidity.

On the other hand, fixed acidity doesn’t seem to influence quality much, as the samples have a median fixed acidity of around 8 across all qualities. Let’s see whether the same is true for citric acid levels.

That’s surprising! Although the fixed acidity doesn’t have influence over quality, citric acid seems to greatly affect it. We can see that the wine samples with the least quality have the lowest median amount of citric acid, while those with the highest quality have the highest median amount of citric acid.

There also seems to be a general decreasing trend for pH and fixed acidity. The samples with the lowest fixed acidity have the highest pH. I want to see whether we can spot similar trends for volatile acidity and pH. In addition, there are strange small gaps occurring almost periodically.

That’s strange… There seems to be no trend at all when we plot volatile acidity versus pH.

Generally, there’s an increasing trend for citric acid and fixed acidity. However, after doing some research, I discovered that citric acid is counted as part of the fixed acidity. This is why it’s logical that as the amount of citric acid increases, the fixed acidity increases as well. Interestingly, there are especially long vertical lines at the citric acid values of 0, 0.25 and 0.5. There’s a wide range of fixed acidity values at these citric acid values, but why?

The fixed acidity also seems to have an effect on density. This is probably for the same reason as residual sugar has an effect on density, because as the amount of acids increase, the mass increases, adding more density.

This one seems to be another dead end. Alcohol percentage doesn’t seem to influence the pH of a wine at all.

Residual sugar also doesn’t seem to be affecting the quality. What about the density?

Density and quality appear to be slightly related through this boxplot. I can see that the samples with the highest quality tend to have the lowest density, while those with the highest quality have the highest density. I wonder whether alcohol percentage influences density, and whether it subsequently affects quality as well.

That’s unexpected! I thought that as alcohol percentage increases, the density would increase. However, it turns out that the contrary is true, as the density is highest when the alcohol percentage is very low, and the density is lowest when the alcohol percentage is very high. This would suggest that having a lower alcohol percentage corresponds to lower quality. Let’s check if this is true.

My prediction is half true. While the correlation between price and quality is clearly positive when the quality is 6 and greater, there doesn’t seem to be evidence of correlation when the quality is 3, 4, or 5. Since volatile acidity and alcohol both seem to affect quality, this raises the question: are volatile acidity and alcohol correlated in some way?

And the anwer is no. These two qualities seem to be independent from one another.

The wine samples with a quality of 5 or greater seem to decrease slightly in median amount of chloride. It’s a very small correlation, however.

pH and quality also have a weak negative correlation!

I want to explore whether the amount of sulphates affects the amount of free and total sulfur dioxide.

Strange… while the text file states that sulphates can contribute to the amount of sulfur dioxide in wine, this does not appear to be the case, according to the plots. We can see that most of the samples have sulphate amounts between 0.375 and 1. When we omit the top 5% of values from both the x and y axes, we can see a distinction between both graphs. While the free sulfur dioxide seems to have certain repeated values, resulting in horizontal lines across the plot, the total sulfur dioxide values are more dispersed.

Quality seems to be influenced by sulphates as well! The median amount of sulphates is highest for samples with a wine quality of 8, and lowest for those with a quality of 3.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the

My main feature of interest, the wine quality, varied depending on the other features. I discovered that alcohol, citric acid, and sulphates have a positive influence over quality, while density, chlorides, pH and volatile acidity negativelyinfluence quality. Meanwhile, the fixed acidity and residual sugar have no effect on quality.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

Yes. I discovered that residual sugar and fixed acidity have a moderate positive correlation with density, while alcohol has a negative correlation with density. In addition, there was no correlation between pH and alcohol, volatile acidity and alcohol, or volatile acidity and pH. I was surprised that there is no correlation between sulphates and free sulfur dioxide or sulphates and total sulfur dioxide. Lastly, the fixed acidity has a negative moderate correlation with pH.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

None of my numeric variables had strong relationships (a correlation coefficient greater than 0.7), and the strongest realtionship was the one pH and fixed acidity, with a correlation factor of approximately -0.68.

Multivariate Plots Section

The trend we saw between quality and alcohol and between quality and density is much more clear here. Generally, samples with lower quality seem to be concentrated on the left where they have lower alcohol percentage and higher density, while those with quality of 6 or more are concentrated on the right, with lower density and higher alcohol percentage.

Holding the density constant, wine samples with higher fixed acidity are of higher quality. In contrast, if we hold the fixed acidity constant, we can see that the samples with higher density receive a lower score of quality than those with lower density.

Our strongest relationship, that between citric acid and fixed acidity, doesn’t yield much when compared with quality. We still see the positive correlation between citric acid and quality, because as the amount of citric acid increases, so does the quality.

Multivariate Analysis

Yes, fixed acidity and density seemed to strengthen each other. Although we didn’t see a strong correlation between fixed acidity and quality in the bivariate analysis, plotting fixed acidity against density revealed that the wines with the highest quality typically have low density and high fixed acidity.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

Yes, I discovered an intriguing relationship between density and alcohol, where they both influence quality in opposing ways.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

Alcohol has a negative correlation with density, meaning that, as the alcohol percentage increases, the density decreases. Furthermore, quality tends to increase as the alcohol increases and the density decreases.

Plot Two

Description Two

This box plot shows that higher median amounts of citric acid have higher quality.

Plot Three

Description Three

This graph shows that density has a positive correlation with density, and that they both have an effect on quality. Holding density constant, samples with higher fixed acidity have higher quality. Holding fixed acidity constant, samples with higher densities have lower ratings. ——

Reflection

I performed exploratory data analysis on the red wine dataset, which includes 11 features collected from 1599 samples of red wine and a quality score for each sample. I found many relations that made sense, such as those between pH and fixed acidity, or citric acid and fixed acidity. On the other hand, many relations buffled me, such as those between sulphates and free/total sulfur dioxide, which had no correlation despite what the text file had said. Ultimately, my goal was to discover which factors most strongly affected wine quality and determined whether it will taste good or not. I discovered that these factors include alcohol, density, citric acid, and fixed acidity.

One of the struggles I went through was the lack of abundant data in the dataset. There were too few observations, and most of them had an average quality of 5 or 6, which made it difficult to determine which factors can lead to a high wine quality of 7 or 8. In addition, there was a lot of missing data in the dataset, which also proved to be an obstacle when trying to find patterns, as in some instances, there were barely any observations for red wine with a quality of 3 or 8.

In the future, if more observations can be added to the dataset, it would be much easier to find a more definitive answer to the question of what makes a wine sample taste good, as clearer patterns would arise in the data and they would be much more representative of the entire population.
